english:
  title: Record of the Chukseok Tower in Jinju
  author: Ha Ryun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The construction of towers and pavilions may seem but a minor concern of those who govern, yet through their rise and fall we may discern the state of the people's hearts and the condition of the world. When the world's fortune waxes and wanes, so too do the sorrows and joys that dwell in human hearts, and so the towers follow in their rise and fall. Thus, from a single tower's flourishing or decay, we may know the heart of a valley's people; from the heart of a valley's people, we may know the state of an age. How then can we dismiss this as a mere trifle?

    I have long held this conviction, and now, witnessing the fate of Chukseok Tower in my own village, my belief is deepened. The tower stands above a stone cliff south of Yongdu Temple. In my youth, I often climbed to its height and gazed across the expanse below. The tower's structure was grand and spacious, commanding views that stretched to infinity—the great river flowing beneath, countless peaks arrayed beyond, the mulberry fields and humble dwellings interspersed with pavilions and flowering trees. Green cliffs and crimson precipices, long inlets and fertile plains, all bordered its sides. The people's spirit was pure, their customs generous. The elderly lived in peace, the young showed respect. Farmers and silkworm maidens labored faithfully at their tasks; filial sons and loving grandsons gave their utmost in service. The sound of pounding pestles echoed through the lanes, and fishermen's songs drifted along the banks. Birds sang freely among the flourishing groves, and fish swam without fear of nets. All creatures within that sphere found their proper place. And when the blossoms bloomed and verdure spread, when cool winds brought clear moonlight, the seasons arrived in their turn. The cycles of waxing and waning, of darkness and light, of shadow and shine succeeded one another without cease, and joy seemed endless.

    As for the tower's name, there exists a record by Tamam Baek, which states that upon the river stones that jutted forth, a tower was built and named Chukseok. It was begun by Kim Kong and completed anew by An Sangheon, both state examination champions. Thus it came to bear this compound name. Among the finest verses written in its praise are six-couplet regulated poems by Myeonjae Jeong and four-couplet lines by Sangheon An. There are also six quatrains by Yuneum Seol, and continuations by such worthies as Geubam Min, Ugok Jeong, and Yizhai Heo—all excellent works, through which we may yet glimpse the refined sensibilities and literary brilliance of our predecessors.

    Unfortunately, in the twilight of the previous dynasty, all institutions fell into decay, frontier defenses grew lax, pirates penetrated deeply inland, and the people descended into suffering. The tower too was consumed by flames. But Heaven opened a new age, and our sacred rulers have succeeded one another in bringing order and instruction to flourish. Their grace has saturated our lands and their authority has extended beyond the seas. Those who once came as marauders now knock at our gates to surrender, and in endless procession bring tribute. The coastal regions are day by day reclaimed and settled, and the populace grows dense once more. Widows and widowers smile again, and the white-haired elders raise their cups to celebrate, saying, "We never imagined we would live to see such peace."

    Yet the sovereign's heart harbors lingering concern, deeming the government's efforts still insufficient. Repeatedly are royal edicts sent forth forbidding the use of the people's labor. Officials dare not initiate even a single project save those concerning agriculture and schools. The village elders—former magistrate Kang Shun, former censor Choi Bokrin, and others—gathered to discuss the matter. They said: "Yongdu Temple has been our region's sacred site since its founding. Chukseok Tower, built upon the river stones, became our greatest landmark, a place through which former generations both entertained envoys and guests and drew down harmonious fortune upon our people. Yet in disrepair for so long, we have lacked the means to restore it. This surely weighs upon all of us."

    They pooled their resources and commissioned Dan Yeong, the temple custodian, to undertake the work. When I reported this to the throne, word came permitting us to proceed. In the twelfth month of the Year of the Monkey, Magistrate Gwon Chung arrived with Judge Park Shi-hyul. After consulting the village elders, in the second month of the following spring, they reconstructed the river embankment, organizing the people into work units, each responsible for a section, thereby eliminating long-standing damage to fields and homes. The work was completed in less than ten days. They then gathered wandering laborers—some fifty in number—spurring them to diligent effort. By autumn, all was complete. The austere structures stood renewed, and the scenic beauty was restored as of old. The present Magistrate Ryu Dam and Judge Yang Shi-gwon have since arrived, adding painted decorations, and moreover have devised plans for irrigation, constructing water wheels and dikes to bring benefit to the people.

    The village elders brought me their complete account, requesting: "All that has been accomplished—the embankment's construction, the tower's restoration—bears your guidance, and now bears the royal seal of special favor. Our region's glory has been magnified beyond measure. The gentlemen's devotion to the people's welfare is evident. Will you not record this so that it endures for generations?"

    I replied: "This is entirely the fruit of your will and effort. What part have I in this?" Yet since I have long found joy in observing how the people's hearts and the state of the world are intertwined, and moved by the elders' intentions, I record here what I have witnessed before and after.

    Moreover, let all who ascend this tower reflect: When you see the grass budding by the water's edge, contemplate Heaven and Earth's heart that gives life to all things, and let no cruelty—not even the breadth of a hair—harm the people's livelihood. When you observe the growing crops in the fields, contemplate Heaven and Earth's heart that nurtures all things, and let no trivial urgency—not even the breadth of a hair—steal the people's planting time. When you witness the fruit trees bearing their increase, contemplate Heaven and Earth's heart that perfects all things, and let no unrighteous desire—not even the breadth of a hair—encroach upon the people's gain. When you see the harvest gathered in the yards, contemplate Heaven and Earth's heart that sustains all things, and let no unlawful taxation—not even the breadth of a hair—plunder the people's wealth. If you extend this heart and enlarge it, if you dare not claim joy for yourself alone but must share it with all people, then everyone will understand that the harmony of the world and the joy in people's hearts truly spring from the sovereign's profound and abundant virtue. All will wish to emulate the blessing that the people of Huafeng once spoke. Thus the elders' earnest labor in bringing this restoration to pass is surely no mere chance.

    I am fortunate that my retirement draws near. I dream of returning to my village on a simple horse, joining the elders on fair days and gentle seasons, ascending this tower to share wine and verse, delighting together in what brings joy, and spending my remaining years in this way. Elders, I hope you will await my return.
  footnotes:
    - '华封人 (Huafeng): In Chinese legend, the people of Huafeng blessed the sage Yao with infinite blessings, exemplifying the harmony between virtuous rule and popular contentment.'
    - 'Sangheon An (安常軒): An examination champion who rebuilt the tower; his name became part of the tower''s historical identity.'
    - The water wheels and irrigation systems mentioned represent practical applications of the restoration's benefits to the farming community.
